init_text:
Is It Wrong to Focus on Animal Welfare When Humans Are Suffering?

Would you be surprised to hear that a study found that research subjects were more upset by stories of a dog beaten by a baseball bat than of an adult similarly beaten? Or that other researchers found that if forced to choose, 40 percent of people would save their pet dog over a foreign tourist.

Why do you think many people are more empathetic toward the suffering of animals than that of people? In your opinion, is it wrong to focus on animal welfare when humans are suffering? Why do you think so?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: it is not at all wrong to focus on animal welfare!

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Humans and animals suffer in many of the same ways.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Many animals fear death as much as humans do.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: If they could, I believe they would fight and scream and try to escape pain, just as we do.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: In addition, if animals could speak, I am sure they would tell us that they feel pain and not to cause them anymore harm.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Understandably, we feel bad when we see a dog or cat that has been abused.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: We can feel like it was us being hurt, and we can almost see ourselves in their situation.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: On the other hand, humans are able to reason, think critically, and express themselves with words.
